After all the treatments i have done, i start the preparation stages for the models.¶
First, i separate the data frame into the data and the target variable.¶
Second, i divide the data into three datasets: for training, validation, and testing of the models.¶
The division for testing and training is 20% for testing and 80% for training.¶
The training data is also divided into 30% for testing and 70% for validation.¶
For all the divisions, I define a constant random number (seed) so that every division that is made will always be the same.¶
In [19]:
# Create X and y variables
X = df.drop("dead_5y", axis=1)
y = df['dead_5y']

# Divide the data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=35)

# Divide the training set into train and dev sets
X_train, X_dev, y_train, y_dev = train_test_split(X_train, y_train, test_size=0.3, random_state=35)

In a moment, i will check the relative balance of the "y" values between the three groups using the chi-squared test, which means i will verify if the "y" values will be distributed relatively evenly between the three groups.¶
In [21]:
def plot_pie_chart(data, title):
    labels = data.index
    plt.pie(data, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)
    plt.axis('equal')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()


train_data = y_train.value_counts(normalize=True)
plot_pie_chart(train_data, 'Train Data Distribution')

dev_data = y_dev.value_counts(normalize=True)
plot_pie_chart(dev_data, 'Validation Data Distribution (Dev)')

test_data = y_test.value_counts(normalize=True)
plot_pie_chart(test_data, 'Test Data Distribution')
In [22]:
outcome_0_counts = [sum(y_train == 0), sum(y_dev == 0), sum(y_test == 0)]
outcome_1_counts = [sum(y_train == 1), sum(y_dev == 1), sum(y_test == 1)]

data_table = [outcome_0_counts, outcome_1_counts]
chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(data_table)

print("Chi-squared test statistic:", chi2)
print("p-value:", p)

Chi-squared test statistic: 0.22450731949964184
p-value: 0.8938175032181039
I can see that there is a tiny difference between these groups, i mean that there is a low significats level.¶
Now Im going to make the same examination on the binar ones in these groups.¶
I will select the categorical variables from the X_train, X_dev, and X_test data sets.¶
Then, I will use these variables to create a contingency table for each categorical variable.¶
And then I will perform the chi-squared test on each contingency table to determine whether there is a significant association between the variables.¶
Finally, I will plot the results of the chi-squared test to make it easier to visualize the associations between the categorical variables.¶
In [23]:
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Select the categorical variables from x_train, x_dev, and x_test
x_train_categorical = X_train[cat_columns]
x_dev_categorical = X_dev[cat_columns]
x_test_categorical = X_test[cat_columns]

# Create a contingency table for each categorical variable
tables = {}
for col in x_train_categorical.columns:
    data_table = pd.crosstab(index=x_train_categorical[col], columns="count")
    data_table["Dev"] = pd.crosstab(index=x_dev_categorical[col], columns="count")
    data_table["Test"] = pd.crosstab(index=x_test_categorical[col], columns="count")
    tables[col] = data_table

    # Perform the chi-squared test on each contingency table
    chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(data_table)
    print(f"Chi-squared test statistic for {col}: {chi2}")
    print(f"p-value for {col}: {p}")
    print("-" * 50)

    # Print the contingency table
    print(f"Contingency table for {col}:")
    print(data_table)
    print("=" * 50)

According to the results, the split that was made between the three data sets is balanced.¶

Now I need to verify if the distribution of the target variable (Y values) is balanced within the training set. If the proportion of 1's in the target variable is less than 15%, then we should perform balancing on the training set.¶

The distribution of the target variable (Y) in our data appears to be imbalanced.¶

Hence, I'll apply resampling techniques (Undersampling, Oversampling, and SMOTE) individually on the preprocessed training dataset.¶

Considering the unbalanced nature of the data, accuracy would not be the most suitable metric to evaluate the performance of the classifier. Instead, we opt to use the AUC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve) to evaluate the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative examples. AUC ranges from 0.5 for a random classifier to 1 for a perfect classifier.¶
In unbalanced datasets, AUC is a preferred metric as it takes into account both the true positive rate (TPR) and false positive rate (FPR) of a binary classification model, making it insensitive to class imbalance. In this case, we chose the logistic regression model and calculated its AUC for each method.¶
With the AUC metric selected as the evaluation method for our binary classification model, i will apply the logistic regression algorithm to each sample method. The AUC metric considers both the true positive rate and false positive rate of the model, providing a single number summary of performance that is not affected by class imbalance. This is particularly important in our case, as class 1 is significantly underrepresented (1.6%) compared to class 0 (98.4%). The AUC metric provides a more accurate measurement of model performance compared to accuracy in unbalanced datasets.¶

lr = LogisticRegression(penalty='l2', C = 1)

# Randomly over sample the minority class
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=46)
X_train_ros, y_train_ros = ros.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Randomly under sample the majority class
rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=46)
X_train_rus, y_train_rus = rus.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Apply Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE)

X_train_smote, y_train_smote = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Based on these results, the Over-sampled model performed better in terms of accuracy, as evidenced by its higher AUC score on both the training and dev datasets. The difference between the training and dev AUC scores for the Over-sampled model is also smaller compared to the Under-sampled model, indicating that the Over-sampled model has better generalization performance and is less likely to overfit the training data.¶
Therefore, the Over-sampled model was chosen as the best option among the three models, despite the SMOTE model having a smaller difference between the training and dev AUC scores, due to its lower overall accuracy. In comparison, the SMOTE model had a significantly lower AUC score on both the training and dev datasets, which makes it a less suitable choice for this scenario.¶

fpr_dev, tpr_dev, thresholds_dev = roc_curve(y_dev, lr_dev_probs)
roc_auc_dev = roc_auc_score(y_dev, lr_dev_probs)

# Generate ROC curve for test set
fpr_test, tpr_test, thresholds_test = roc_curve(y_test, lr_test_probs)
roc_auc_test = roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_test_probs)

# Plot ROC curve for train set
plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, label='Train AUC: %0.2f'% roc_auc_train)

# Plot ROC curve for dev set
plt.plot(fpr_dev, tpr_dev, label='Dev AUC: %0.2f'% roc_auc_dev)

# Plot ROC curve for test set
plt.plot(fpr_test, tpr_test, label='Test AUC: %0.2f'% roc_auc_test)

# Plot the reference line
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')

# Set the axis labels and title
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC curve for Logistic Regression')

# Show the legend
plt.legend(loc='lower right')

# Show the plot
plt.show()
The AUC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic) score is a commonly used metric to evaluate the performance of a binary classifier. In the case of these results, the AUC scores for the train set, dev set, and test set are 0.8158565128415997, 0.7930159622468452, and 0.8023206011758751, respectively.¶
A score of 1.0 represents a perfect classifier, while a score of 0.5 represents a random classifier. A good classifier will have a high AUC score, close to 1.0, indicating that it is able to distinguish between positive and negative classes well.¶
In this case, the train AUC score is higher than the dev and test AUC scores. This is generally expected, as the model has been trained on the training data, and will perform better on that data. However, the difference between the train and dev/test AUC scores is relatively small, indicating that the model is not overfitting the training data, and generalizes well to new data.¶
The AUC scores of 0.79 and 0.80 for the dev and test sets respectively, indicate that the Logistic Regression model is performing well in classifying the target variable based on the input features.¶
